<b>Recent stakeholder activities</b>
<br>Host for the <a href="http://www.ucs.iastate.edu/mnet/cpas/home.html" target="_bank">9th Annual Climate Predictions Application Science Workshop, 1-4 March 2011</a></br>
<br>Several of our Co-Is and letters of support providers are involved in this workshop.  Co-PI Takle and Co-I Anderson are organizing committee members, and the logistical support is being provided by the Bioeconomy Institute, the institution that would house the proposed RISA core management staff.  Co-I Babcock, and letter of support providers Iowa Farm Bureau will participate in a Agricultural Users Panel.  Letter of support provider JAWF will present durint the agricultural theme sessions at the Workshop.  Letter of support providers Senator Joe Bolkcom, Iowa League of Cities, Iowa Association of Regional Councils, Iowa Water Center, and American Planners Association Iowa Chapter is assisting in organizing and publicizing an outreach event for State and Federal officials with concerns about flood risk next spring.  The event will include outreach activities by <a href="http://www.cpc.noaa.gov/" target="_blank"CPC</a>,<a href="http://www.crh.noaa.gov/ncrfc/"> NC RFC </a>, and <a href="http://www.crh.noaa.gov/dmx"> DSM NWSFO</a>.  It will be hosted by the <a href="http://climate.engineering.iastate.edu"> ISU Climate Science Program </a> and MiCCA Affiliate the <a href="http://www.iowafloodcenter.org/"> Iowa Flood Center </a>
<br><br>
<br> Participant in the series of outreach forums <a href="http://www.cgrer.uiowa.edu/calendar/2010/10/10252010(1).htm" target="_blank"> Anatomy of Iowa Floods: Preparing for the Future</a></br>
<br>Co-PI Takle and Co-I Anderson participated in 11 outreach forums across the state of Iowa that were designed to facilitate discussion among climate scientists, hydrologists, state government agencies, local community planners and government officials, and the public.  Topics of discussion included recent understanding of changing climate conditions and their potential impact on flood intensity, new tools that enable communities to identify flood risk, state programs, incentives, and planning tools to improve the ability of communities to mitigate flood impacts, and novel local ordinances and mitigation approaches that proactive communities have taken.  From this effort, a core MiCCA stakeholder network was developed that includes letters of support from Rebuild Iowa Office, Iowa Association of Regional Councils, Iowa League of Cities, Iowa Linn County Board of Supervisors, Iowa Deparment of Natural Resources, Iowa Water Center, and Iowa Senator Joe Bolkcom.
<br><br>
<br>Lead Participant in the EPA-sponsored pilot project (Phase I coordinator)<a href="Iowa.Climate.Change.Pilot.Plan.pdf" target="_blank">Iowa Climate Change Adaptation and Resilience Pilot</a>
<br>The stated goal of the pilot is "Working in Iowa, identify barriers to and incentives for considering regional effects of climate change in hazard mitigation and other community planning processes."  The pilot project involved many in the MiCCA community planning stakeholder network: Iowa League of Cities, Iowa Association of Regional Councils, Iowa Flood Center, Rebuild Iowa Office and Iowa Department of Natural Resources.  The network was extended by working closely with city planners in Ames and Coralville, county planners in Story County, the Iowa State Association of Counties, and US Army Corps Rock Island District.  
<br>One outcome of the pilot is a report that contains a list of recommendations of how to improve community resilience to hazards (particularly floods).  The draft findings and recommendations of the pilot project (a final report will be available after Dec 4) are
<ul>
<li>Communities are at the forefront of adapting to climate change
<li>Land use is a primary determinant of community climate change adaptation capacity.
<li>Communities need to integrate planning processes, specifically hazard mitigation and comprehensive land use planning.
<li>Climate change data must be formatted and distributed in a way that is accessible and usable by local planners.
<li>Local planners need to increase skill sets to effectively utilize climate change data.
<li>Federal and state programs and policies should give communities incentives to integrate planning processes, specifically hazard mitigation and comprehensive land use planning.
<li>Investment decisions should take a regional perspective and be integrated across infrastructure types and sectors to realize co-benefits. 
<li>Communities should prioritize strategies that meet hazard mitigation planning requirements, incorporate low regret adaptation measures, and produce symbiotic outcomes. 
<li>Federal and state programs should provide prioritized funding for communities and projects that meet hazard mitigation planning requirements, incorporate low regret adaptation measures, and produce symbiotic outcomes. 
<li>Increase federal funding and focus on pre-disaster planning for community resilience and sustainability.
<li>Remove policy and knowledge barriers to including climate change science in hazard mitigation planning.
</ul>

